^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are some definite issues with the bidding here. Everything through the double was fine and Sandy certainly can pass, but might consider bidding 2C with her nice suit (although better if 6 cards). So pass and 1@S were fine. However, now Stan has a problem. With such a strong hand, their side could easily have game. Whether and whether is not clear.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It could be in spades, it could be in hearts, or it might conceivably be in NT. Trying to solve the problem by bidding 2H is not the way to bid. 2@H bid is a "double and correct." |
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|When you make a takeout double partner assumes initially you have the 3 other suits covered. Then, if after partner chooses a suit and you change suits, that is called a "double and correct" because you are "correcting" partner's bid to your own suit.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A double and correct has a specific meaning. it shows a good hand (at least a good 16). Stan certainly has that. However, it also shows a  good 6-card suit, which Stan does not have. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So what should Stan bid? The best bid would be 2@C - cue bid of opponents' suit. If Stan had a club stopper, then 1N would work. An original 1N bid in the balancing seat would show 11-14. But a double and "correct" to 1N shows about 15-18. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, Stan is both slightly too strong and lacks a club stopper. If Stan had 17 or 18, I might bid 1N anyway with his hand, because based on the auction, it is quite possible partner has some clubs (clubs were not raised or rebid). But 1N with his hand is a bit of a misbid for 2 reasons.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|He is too strong and he lacks a club stopper. So the way to solve the problem is to bid 2@C. The meaning of this cue bid is "partner I have a good hand but am not sure what to do", "please help me out." Over 2C Roberta has several choices. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|2N would probably be my choice. That would show a club stopper and around 6-9 points. 3@S is another choice but you could easily miss 3N. Stan should then bid 3@S (which is forcing) and Roberta would bid 4@S.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|2@S by Stan is possible as well - it is a bit of an underbid. 3@S by Stan, however, is an overbid particularly because he only has 3 card support.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


