^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This was another interesting and hard to bid hand. Let me just suggest the following to Stan. If you intended to bid 4@S over 4@H, then you should bid 4@S right away. One of the things experts do is try to anticipate likely auctions and plan their bidding accordingly. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Most experts would decide, as Stan did, that it is right to bid 4S over 4@H. Granted, it is conceivable it could go 3@H-3@S-all pass. But 3@S is only right if the auction goes that way and you make exactly 3@S which is pretty unlikely.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, given Stan (very reasonably) decided he was going to bid 4@S over 4@H, he should bid 4@S right away to make it harder for us to figure out what to do. On this hand it is likely to make no difference as Sandy is probably doubling. |
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But it will often make it much tougher. Remember, it is always better to bid more in competitive situations (assuming you have the distribution) because you want to make it harder for the opponents to make the right decision. The less room they have, the more difficulty they will have in guessing correctly.|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The more room they have, the better chance they have. N/S do make 4@H. They lose 2 hearts and 1 spade for sure. If I guess the heart suit, I make 4, but it is likely I will lose 3 hearts. The point is, whether 4@S is right or not on this hand, once Stan decides he is going to bid it, he should bid it right away.|
